I was raised by a single mother, studying abroad isn’t cheap, so I decided to move to Canada, with my girlfriend.”

The feeling in my organization is that the social cognition in the developed world is getting so bad that it will soon get us in trouble. Our social networks are deteriorating beck to a point where they were before modern technology, and many young people are confused by it. Though some of these ideas only applies to Canada (England for example is usually considered a model for its free press, freedom of speech and press and for its U.K. police set-up).

While we cannot make a big impact on each other’s individual lives, we can at least, as a collective of young adults, O2Y and the rest of the American, European and even global youth community, point to civil society and the European Union and say, “This is your opportunity to take control.” The development of companies such as Facebook, Twitter and other social media services and platforms has enlightened a new way of communicating. Young people, especially have rediscovered the ways of association, and they have created strong networks to express themselves.
